};
```



## Common Mistakes

- Blindly accepting AI suggestions without security review, assuming AI-generated code is inherently safe
- Pasting production code or sensitive data (customer data, secrets, proprietary logic) into AI prompts without sanitization
- Not integrating automated security scanning into the development workflow, relying solely on manual review
- Using the same security review standards for manually written code while giving AI-generated code a pass
- Hardcoding credentials, API keys, or configuration values that AI suggests in examples
- Failing to validate and sanitize user inputs in code that AI generates for data processing
- Ignoring privacy implications and regulatory requirements when using AI tools with company data
- Not learning common vulnerability patterns, making it impossible to spot dangerous AI suggestions


## Best Practices

- Treat all AI-generated code as potentially vulnerable until reviewed by security-aware personnel
- Integrate automated SAST (Static Application Security Testing) tools into CI/CD pipelines to catch vulnerabilities before deployment
- Implement secret scanning in pre-commit hooks and CI to prevent hardcoded credentials from entering version control
- Establish clear organizational policies defining what data can and cannot be shared with AI tools
- Create AI-specific code review checklists that include security validation criteria for injection risks, secret exposure, and compliance
- Use environment variables and secrets management solutions instead of hardcoded values—train yourself to reject AI suggestions with hardcoded secrets
- Enable IDE security plugins that provide real-time feedback on vulnerability patterns in AI-generated code
- Maintain human oversight and accountability: the developer is always responsible for code quality and security regardless of origin
- Regularly update security training to address new vulnerability patterns that AI tools might propagate
- Configure AI tools with privacy settings that minimize data retention and exposure, especially for sensitive projects

